{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d5f80ccb-a710-464a-a3a0-08e5cdb83220","content":"Here's the correct skip attribute for each framework:\n\n**MSTest**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**xUnit (v2)**\n```csharp\n[Fact(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n[Theory(Skip = \"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**xUnit (v3)**\nSame as v2, but also supports runtime skip via `Assert.Skip(\"reason\")` inside the test body.\n\n**NUnit**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\n**TUnit**\n```csharp\n[Skip(\"Reason for skipping\")]\n```\n\nAll frameworks require a reason string. The skipped tests will appear in results as \"skipped\" or \"ignored\" (not \"passed\" or \"failed\"), so they remain visible in reports.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aaf45e0a-e19f-4b8a-8b3d-bac59a3e1d1f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about skip/ignore attributes across MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit. This is a straightforward knowledge question - I can answer directly without needing tools.","outputTokens":253,"requestId":"4C14:A0D2E:DCD55A:1130962:6A012D4F"},"id":"ce7826de-c1b8-4f2c-be69-2666482a9e9d","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:13:58.348Z","parentId":"818d7fda-7a8f-4744-84e7-6d25c3a84c8c"}
